Exercise instructions¶

This is the template for the third exercise. The purpose of this exercise is to familiarize yourself with the basics of unsupervised learning by using the agglomerative hierarchical clustering and k-means clustering algorithms to find patterns.

This exercise uses the seeds dataset, available on moodle as seeds.csv. The features are all numeric. They quantify the measurements related to the geometrical properties of wheat grains. The feature names are listed in the table below.

| Feature | Type | :--- | ---: | Area | Numeric (float) | Perimeter | Numeric (float) | Compactness | Numeric (float) | Length | Numeric (float) | Width | Numeric (float) | Asymmetry Coefficient | Numeric (float) | Length Groove | Numeric (float)


In real applications, visualizing various aspects of the data the data and data scrubbing are important steps. However, in this exercise you can treat the data as given, and focus on the unsupervised methods. REMEMBER, this step can never be neglected in the real world.

# YOUR CODE
#Z-score standardization for dataframe
seeds_standardized = (seeds - seeds.mean()) / seeds.std()
#print(seeds_standardized)

#Fit to pca model with 2 components for 2d visualization
pca = PCA(n_components = 2)
seeds_2D = pca.fit_transform(seeds_standardized)

#Visualize with scatter plot
plt.scatter(seeds_2D[:, 0], seeds_2D[:, 1])

#Draw some ellipsies for fun
ax = plt.gca()
ellipse1 = Ellipse(xy = (-2, 0), height = 2, width = 5, angle = 305, edgecolor = 'black', facecolor = 'none', linewidth = 2)
ellipse2 = Ellipse(xy = (2, 0), height = 2, width = 5, angle = 45, edgecolor = 'black', facecolor = 'none', linewidth = 2)
ax.add_patch(ellipse1)
ax.add_patch(ellipse2)
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.title('2D PCA Projection')
plt.show()

Standardizing the values in the dataframe is important for the principal component analysis to work, since pca is very sensitive towards variance.

Part 2a: Agglomerative hierarchical clustering theory¶

Explain briefly the different linkage criterion values.

  • Single: Single linkage represents the shortest distance between two clusters
  • Average: Average linkage represents the average dissimilarity of data points of two clusters
  • Complete: Complete linkage represents the longest distance between two clusters
  • Ward: Ward's method uses squared euclidian distance to compute cluster distances

Explain the silhouette coefficient (silhouette_score).

The silhoutte value of a data point is a real number between -1 and +1 assigned to a data point which represents how well the point fits into the cluster it's a member of. The silhoutte coefficient (or score) is the mean of the silhoutte values for all data points in a dataset.

In [8]:
n = 2
no_in = 100
no_out = 500
labels = np.concatenate((np.zeros(no_in), np.ones(no_out)))

inner_cluster = np.random.randn(no_in, 2)*0.1
theta = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, no_out)
outer_cluster = np.array([np.cos(theta), np.sin(theta)]).T + np.random.randn(no_out, 2)*0.1
data = np.vstack((inner_cluster, outer_cluster))

score = silhouette_score(data, labels)

plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
plt.title(f'{n} clusters\nSilhouette coefficient: {score:.3f}')
for c in range(n):
    plt.scatter(data[labels==c, 0], data[labels==c, 1], alpha=0.5)
    
plt.show()

In the figure above, why is the silhouette coefficient close to zero even though the clusters are clearly distinct?

(Optional) What would be a better way to assess this clustering?

The sklearn method used to compute the mean silhoutte value (silhoutte_score) might differ in implementation. For instance the choice of distance metric used to compute the individual silhoutte scores affects the outcome, the datasets contain both negative and positive value pairs as well as negative-positive and positive-negative value pairs, which might in turn lead to skewed results.

Cluster the standardized data into 2-10 clusters using agglomerative hierarchical clustering.

In [24]:
#Perform agglomerative hierarchical clusterings
for clusters in range(2, 11):
    print('Number of clusters: ' + str(clusters))
    
    #Single linkage
    single_clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = clusters, linkage = 'single').fit(seeds_standardized)
    single_score = silhouette_score(seeds_standardized, single_clustering.labels_)
    print('Single linkage: ' + str(single_score))

    #Average linkage
    average_clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = clusters, linkage = 'average').fit(seeds_standardized)
    average_score = silhouette_score(seeds_standardized, average_clustering.labels_)
    print('Average linkage: ' + str(average_score))
    
    #Complete linkage
    complete_clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = clusters, linkage = 'complete').fit(seeds_standardized)
    complete_score = silhouette_score(seeds_standardized, complete_clustering.labels_)
    print('Complete linkage: ' + str(complete_score))

    #Ward linkage
    ward_clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = clusters, linkage = 'ward').fit(seeds_standardized)
    ward_score = silhouette_score(seeds_standardized, ward_clustering.labels_)
    print('Ward linkage: ' + str(ward_score))

centroids = []

#Perform the kmeans clustering with 2-10 clusters and store centroids in above array
for clusters in range(2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = clusters).fit(seeds_standardized)
    kmeans_labels = kmeans.labels_
    kmeans_score = silhouette_score(seeds_standardized, kmeans_labels)
    print(kmeans.cluster_centers_)
    centroids.append(kmeans.cluster_centers_)
    print('Amount of clusters: ' + str(clusters))
    print('Silhoutte coefficient: ' + str(kmeans_score))

The 4 best silhoutte coefficients are for clusterings with either 2, 3, 4 or 6 clusters. The reason it's important to transform the centroids with pca is that by default they are 6-dimensional and couldn't be displayed in the 2d-graph that way.

Part 4 (BONUS): Filling in missing labels using clustering¶

In this bonus exercise, you're given a dataset with almost all of the labels missing. This is the starting point in semi-supervised learning. Semi-supervised learning in general is beyond the scope of this course, but if you want you can learn more about it, starting e.g. on the sklearn page for semi-supervised learning. This exercise does not require researching semi-supervised learning, however.

The dataset used in this exercise is a slightly modified version of the wine dataset. The features quantify chemical properties of wine, grown around the same area in Italy. They are divided to three different classes, simply called 1, 2 and 3 here. The feature names and their data types are listed in the table below. Use the modified dataset on Moodle, with the filename wine_missing_labels.csv

| Feature | Type | :--- | ---: | Alcohol | Numeric (float) | Malic acid | Numeric (float) | Ash | Numeric (float) | Alcalinity of ash | Numeric (float) | Magnesium | Numeric (integer) | Total phenols | Numeric (float) | Flavanoids | Numeric (float) | Nonflavanoid phenols | Numeric (float) | Proanthocyanins | Numeric (float) | Color intensity | Numeric (float) | Hue | Numeric (float) | OD280/OD315 of diluted wines | Numeric (float) | Proline | Numeric (integer)


First, visualize the first two principal components of the dataset in a scatter plot, showing the labels real for data points you were given. Try to see if the labels look like they belong in what look like clusters on the plot.

In [14]:
wine_data = pd.read_csv('wine_missing_labels.csv')
wine_labels = pd.read_csv('wine_labels.csv')
wine_data = wine_data.drop('Label', axis = 1)
wine_pca = PCA(n_components = 2).fit_transform(wine_data)

plt.scatter(wine_pca[:, 0], wine_pca[:, 1], c = wine_labels['Label'])
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.title('2D PCA Projection')
plt.show()

There are disinct clusters, although the middle one overlaps with both of the neighbouring clusters.

Your task is to use clustering to assign labels to the rows that have a missing value as their label. Do this by first clustering all of the data, and then filling in the missing labels based on which clusters the data points with known labels tend to fit in.

Use whichever clustering methods you prefer. You can cluster the data into 3 clusters because you have 3 known labels, but you could also try a higher number of clusters that you can then merge.

The details of how exactly you decide which rows get assigned which label are up to you - you can get creative. Describe and justify your thought process.


You are also given the full labels for the dataset in a separate file called wine_labels.csv. Plot the real labels next to the labels that your clustering attempts predicted.

Finally, compute the adjusted Rand index for labels predicted by your clustering solutions and the real labels, and display it along the scatter plots. Rand index is a measure of similarity between two partitions of a set of elements. Adjusted Rand index is corrected for chance using the maximum and expected values of Rand index. Optionally, you can learn more about the Rand index e.g. on the Wikipedia page for Rand index. Here you can simply use the sklearn.metrics.adjusted_rand_score method imported at the beginning of this notebook without further understanding of it.

Hint: you should get something over 0.8

In [21]:
#Z-score standardization
wine_standardized = (wine_data - wine_data.mean()) / wine_data.std()

#Kmeans clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 3).fit(wine_data)
kmeans_labels = kmeans.labels_

#Plot the predicted labels as well as the real labels
plt.scatter(wine_pca[:, 0], wine_pca[:, 1], c = kmeans_labels)
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.title('2D PCA Projection with kmeans clustering')
plt.show()

plt.scatter(wine_pca[:, 0], wine_pca[:, 1], c = wine_labels['Label'])
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.title('2D PCA Projection, real labels')
plt.show()

#Compute and display rand score
rand_score = adjusted_rand_score(wine_labels['Label'], kmeans_labels)
print('Adjusted rand score for kmeans labeling: ' + str(rand_score))

Adjusted rand score for kmeans labeling: 0.37111371823084754

I deciced to go with kmeans clustering since it got a better silhoutte coefficient in the previous exercises, across the board. The amount of clusters chosen was 3.
